    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
        [Chapter 2, starting p.69]: 12.5
        </p>
      </statement>
       <solution>
          <p>
            Note that, if <m> S</m> is not normal, you do not need to do anything else other than explain why <m> S</m> is not normal. 

If <m> S</m> is normal: The problem asks you to identify the quotient group <m> G/S</m>. 
What does ``identify" mean? You need to establish an isomorphism with a familiar group using FIT. 
 You will have to guess the group and the homomorphism! Once you guess it, make sure to check that 
 it is indeed a homomorphism. To argue that <m> S</m> is normal, you may simply argue that <m> S</m> is the kernel.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

