<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
    [Problem B]
    Consider the multiplicative group <m> G=\mathbb F^{\times}</m> of nonzero elements in a field <m> \mathbb F</m> with <m> n</m> elements. 
    </p>
    <ol>
<li>
  <p>
    Prove that the set <m> H=\{x^2\mid x\in G\}</m> is a subgroup of <m> G</m> . 
  </p>
</li>
<li>
  <p>
 Determine the index <m> [G\colon H]</m> . (The fact that <m> \mathbb F</m> is a field is important here. 
 Make sure to explain where it is used.)
    </p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
   Assume <m> -1\notin H</m> . Prove that for each <m> x\in G</m> either <m> x\in H</m> or <m> -x\in H</m> .  Make sure to explain why the hypothesis <m> -1\notin H</m> is relevant. 
</p>
</li>
  </ol>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        For (a) I recommend that you construct a homomorphism <m> \varphi</m> such that <m> H=\text{Im}(\varphi)</m> . 
        Then you can use the known fact that the image of a homomorphism is a subgroup. 
        However, make sure to prove <m> \varphi</m> is a homomorphism.  For (b), you need to know <m> |H|</m> .  
        Think about using  FIT. If you can use FIT to show that <m> G/N\cong H</m> for some <m> N</m> that you will have to figure out, 
        then you have <m> |H|=|G/N|=|G|/|N|</m> . For (c), it may be useful to think about the cosets of <m> H</m> . 
      </p>
    </hint>
</exercise>
